Sam Pirkl and Sean Beckford

This redesign makes good use of encapsulation because it separates all the
code involving the implementation of the Thing objects into a Thing class (or
extensions of the Thing class). It supports data hiding because all instance 
variables are made private. It also uses inheritance to make an ThingB an
extension of the Thing class. So ThingB "is a" Thing, but it has a few
differences in its implementation from the Thing class. It also uses
polymorphism to override function calls to maybeTurn(), because the ThingA
and ThingB objects have different reasons for why they turn. 

This design makes adding new types of Thing objects very easy because it
extends a pre-existing class, so the new Thing inherits all the variables
of the other class. So you don't need to rewrite the logic for how the Thing
moves, you just need to use those for when the Thing needs to turn.

The moveThings() function in the ThingList class has a polymorphic function
call maybeTurn(). For each Thing object in the ThingList (which could be a 
ThingA, ThingB, or ThingC), it calls maybeTurn() for each of those. This is 
essential because the program doesn't need to know what kind of Thing object 
it's referencing, it just needs each Thing to turn with its own turn mechanics.